3 With QFRM package

Pricing of Vanilla and Exotic Option Contracts Option pricing (financial derivatives) techniques mainly following textbook ‘Options, Futures and Other Derivatives’, 9ed by John C.Hull, 2014. Prentice Hall. Implementations are via binomial tree option model (BOPM), Black-Scholes model, Monte Carlo simulations, etc. This package is a result of Quantitative Financial Risk Management course (STAT 449 and STAT 649) at Rice University, Houston, TX, USA, taught by Oleg Melnikov, statistics PhD student, as of Spring 2015.

o <- Opt(Style = "European", Right = "Call", S0 = 160, ttm = 3, K = 150) # An OptPx object
(o <- BOPM_Eu(OptPx(o, r = 0.18232, NSteps = 3)))$PxBT # option price value
[1] 76.42035

This function only recombining symmetric binomial tree. In HW case, we need to construct asymmetric one.

Note: Opt arguments

4 With asymmetric binomial tree

For pseudo probability (risk-neutral probability), we have

\[ p \triangleq \frac{R-d}{u-d} \] where R denotes to the gross return

# define pseudo probability
p_prob <- function(R, u, d) {
  p <- (R - d) / (u - d)
  return(p)
}
# calculate pseudo probability
p_prob(R = 1.2, u = 1.5, d = 0.5)
[1] 0.7

By the backward induction, we have call option price \(\mathrm{C}\)

\[ \mathrm{C} = \frac{\sum_{j=0}^{n}\binom{n}{j}p^{n}(1-p)^{n-j}\times \max(0,S_{0}u^{n}d^{n-j}-X)}{R^{n}} \] where \(j = 0,...,n\)

# define function
# Input: S:'stock price', n:'number of periods', X:'strike price', u:'retrun when price goes up, a multiplier', d:'retrun when price goes down, a multiplier', R:'gross return'
opt_price <- function(S, n, X, u, d, R) {
  p <- (R - d) / (u - d) # calculate the pseudo probability
  tree <- c() # create empty vector
  for (i in 0:n) {
    tree[i] <- choose(n, i) * (p^i) * (1 - p)^(n - i) * max(0, S * (u^i) * d^(n - i) - X) # store payoff in the vector
  }
  return(sum(tree) / (R^n)) # calculate the option price and return
}

Notice that the gross resturn is equivelent to

\[ R \triangleq e^{\hat{r}} \]

where \(\hat{r}\) is the continuously compounded riskless rate per period

Thus, the call price is

opt_price(S = 160,n = 3,X = 150,u = 1.5,d = 0.5,R = 1.2)
[1] 85.06944

Also, we have put option price \(\mathrm{P}\) with price formula \[ \mathrm{P} = \frac{\sum_{j=0}^{n}\binom{n}{j}p^{n}(1-p)^{n-j}\times \max(0,X-S_{0}u^{n}d^{n-j})}{R^{n}} \]

thus we can add type argument from call/put

For call option price:

opt_price(S = 160, n = 3, X = 150, u = 1.5, d = 0.5, R = 1.2, type = "call")
[1] 85.06944

For put option price:

opt_price(S = 160, n = 3, X = 150, u = 1.5, d = 0.5, R = 1.2, type = "put")
[1] 11.875

Validate the put price with put call parity

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} C+Xe^{-rT} &= P+S \\ where \ \ C &= call \ premium \\ Xe^{-rT} &= present \ value \ of \ the \ strike \\ P &= put \ premium \\ S &= the \ current \ price \ of \ the \ underline \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

85.06944 + 150/(1.2^3) - 160
[1] 11.875
